Context / problem
AI conversation exports from platforms like ChatGPT and Claude accumulate rapidly into large, fragmented JSON files that are effectively inaccessible to the users who generated them. For people who use these tools intensively over years, this represents a significant loss of personal intellectual history.
Specific question or claim
Can a non-technical user design and deploy a functional personal knowledge retrieval system built entirely from their own AI conversation data, at zero cost?
Approach / method
Using iterative AI-assisted development with no prior coding knowledge, a browser-based tool was designed and built to parse, index, and search approximately 315MB of conversation exports spanning three years and over 1,000 conversations across multiple platforms. All processing runs locally in the browser with no server, no API dependency, and no cost.
Key result
A fully functional search and retrieval interface was produced as a single portable HTML file, supporting multi-term search, relevance scoring, timeline filtering, in-conversation search, and personal tagging — deployable on any device with a browser.
Implication / so-what
This demonstrates that meaningful personal data sovereignty — owning and querying your own AI interaction history — is achievable without technical expertise, institutional access, or financial resources.
